WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
 Hello and welcome to another walkthrough for Django for everybody. In this walkthrough, we're going to take a look at the sample code called WELL.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:22.000
 The name WELL is based on a long-time early pre-internet forum in Berkeley, California, so you can go look up the WELL.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:33.000
 The basic idea of the WELL is it looks exactly like myarts. It's pretty much a clone of myarts.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:47.000
 If you recall myarts, you had articles-crud, article, article-submit, article-crud, delete, just a basic article-crud.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:01:00.000
 The only difference between this and the WELL is there's a search box here, so I can search for things that have YADA in them, and then I can clear the search box, and that's it.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:08.000
 First, let's observe something that we can observe from the outside when I do a search.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:24.000
 The search is a get parameter, and the reason for that is that get URLs are idempotent, so that basically says go to my blog and find all the blog posts that mention 123.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:39.000
 I could put that in as, let me clear my search here, and I could do, let's search for DSS search here.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:51.000
 This URL is the search for the ones that are DSS, so now I've bookmarked both these, and now that is going to be a short link to the ones that say DSS.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:57.000
 So what I'm going to do is clear this search now, and this will show you something about idempotent URLs.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:04.000
 I'm going to say yada456, I was here, submit.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:14.000
 So now I have two that have the word yada in the title, but watch what happens when I go to the URL that I bookmarked.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:27.000
 So I see now two posts. So the key of idempotent is not that you get the exact same page, you get the exact same logical page, not the exact same text every time.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.000
 It's not like a cache that just clones the text.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:45.000
 You know, I go to this before, and then I go to it now, and if I then delete this one, and then I go to this again, that's the ones that have yada in them.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
 And so that's why we're going to do a search for yada.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:57.000
 And it's really quite simple here. I'll show you everything, but let's just start with an inspect element so you can see what's going on here.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:03.000
 The first little trick here is you can construct that URL, and this goes way back.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:15.000
 This goes way back to a form without a method equals post, which means it's a get method, which means that this name equals search becomes...

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:27.000
 It just goes on, and it does a get request. So instead of doing a post request, which we've been doing for weeks now, this does a get request, and it adds a get parameter.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:36.000
 And so we've got in our view, our main view, that is well, we're seeing a get parameter. It is not a different view. We're getting a view with a get parameter.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:50.000
 And that also means that if I inspect element on this little undo icon that I made, all I'm doing is I'm making a link to /well without the parameter.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
 So it's super easy. So like get rid of the search is just go to a different URL. I could have done it...

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:03.000
 Well, it is an anchor tag. It's a href tag. Look. So I've just gone to well, and it's not there. It's the same view.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:19.000
 So searching, and if you were to go and take a look at how Amazon or Google, they do search, they're forever putting that stuff in the URL so that you can then bookmark them.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
 And so I'll get rid of those bookmarks later. But you see how that is idempotent.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:34.000
 When I said weeks ago, I said get URLs are idempotent. I can now sort of show you in code that we're writing how that works.

